        "Spanish is today the second most spoken language as a native tongue in the world, with more than five hundred million native speakers in twenty-one countries. However, its origins are far more modest: it was born as a dialect of Vulgar Latin spoken by Roman soldiers and settlers on the Iberian Peninsula over two thousand years ago.\n\nAfter the fall of the Roman Empire in the fifth century, the spoken Latin of Hispania began to evolve independently, mixing with the languages of the Visigothic peoples who dominated the peninsula for centuries. Later, the Muslim invasion of 711 introduced thousands of Arabic words that Spanish has retained to this day: almohada (pillow), aceite (oil), azúcar (sugar), alcalde (mayor), and algoritmo (algorithm) are just a few examples. This period of cultural coexistence, known as Al-Ándalus, lasted nearly eight centuries and left an indelible mark on the Spanish vocabulary.\n\nCastilian, as the dialect born in the Kingdom of Castile was called, began to assert itself as a language of prestige during the Reconquista (8th–15th centuries), the process by which the Christian kingdoms of the north gradually reclaimed territories occupied by the Moors. The political unification under the Catholic Monarchs — Isabella of Castile and Ferdinand of Aragon — in the fifteenth century was decisive. In 1492, the same year Columbus reached America, the grammarian Antonio de Nebrija published the first grammar of Castilian, the first of any Romance language. Nebrija wrote with remarkable foresight: 'language has always been the companion of Empire.'\n\nThe conquest of America radically transformed the reach of Spanish. In less than a century, the language spread across a vast territory, from present-day Mexico to Argentina, through Central America and the Caribbean. The colonizers imposed Castilian as the administrative and religious language, although indigenous languages — such as Nahuatl, Quechua, and Guaraní — contributed thousands of words to the American vocabulary: chocolate, tomato, potato, condor, canoe. Spanish in America and Spain evolved separately for centuries, which explains the differences in pronunciation, vocabulary, and grammar that exist today between the various varieties of the language.\n\nThe Real Academia Española, founded in 1713, was created with the aim of fixing and defending the language. Its famous motto, 'it cleans, it fixes, it gives splendor,' reflects that normative spirit. Today, the RAE works in collaboration with the twenty-two national Spanish language academies of the world to adapt the language to the realities of the twenty-first century, from digital language to debates on inclusive language.\n\nSpanish continues to grow. In the United States there are already more than forty million native Spanish speakers, making it the second largest Spanish-speaking country in the world after Mexico. Experts predict that by 2100 there will be more than seven hundred million Spanish speakers. Far from being a language of the past, Spanish is a living language, in constant expansion and transformation.",
